It's here! It's here! It's here!

Do you think that you've got the sharpness and accuracy of Hawkeye, or the memory of Sherlock? Then take the lead here and test your skills. ISTE NIT Durgapur is thrilled to announce the second edition of 'Brain Blogger.'

Get your cognitive skills to work in Round 1 and identify as many symbols and logos as possible from the posters provided, as fast as you can! Dare your eyes in Round 2 and spot differences between two pictures of the same scene taken from some of your favourite movies! But remember, one of the images is real while the other is a copy. 

Block the date for 27th February and you stand a chance to win a cash prize worth Rs. 500!

Contest Rules:-
1. Only one entry per person is allowed.
2. Answers should be strictly in lower case characters with correct spelling. Each correct answer will fetch 10 points.
3. Results will be declared according to the total points scored in both rounds.
4. Commenting on the answers directly would lead to disqualifications. Answers should be given in the link provided.

#iste #brainblogger #funevent #event #brainhacked #brainstormer #mindboggling

"You cannot teach a man anything, you can only help him find it within himself"

The above words remind us of a genius who not only divulged the mysteries of physics and engineering but also took human comprehension beyond the Earth. Born on 15th February, 1564, little the world knew that a prodigy was concealed within the young lutenist from Pisa. As an astronomer, philosopher and mathematician, Galileo Galilei worked on motion, astronomy, strength of materials and development of scientific method. His inventions include the thermoscope and various military compasses. He soon became notorious as the “Father” of modern science, modern physics and observational astronomy.

Remembering him on his 458th birth anniversary, we here at ISTE NIT Durgapur are wholeheartedly grateful to him for shaping our understanding. Every contribution he made will be remembered till the very last.

Three years back, on this day, 40 Indian CRPF Bravehearts were martyred in one of the deadliest terror attacks on security forces which had nearly brought India and Pakistan to the brink of war. Every Indian shed tears on that fateful day after a cowardly attack from the Pakistani side. 

Mourned as the "Black Day" all over the territory, the Pulwama attack brought about a serious blow to the India-Pakistan relations. Retrospecting the courage and valour of all those whose bloodshed purified the patriotic essence of our motherland, we express our utmost dignity and respect to the heroes who brought peace in the lives of our citizens. 

We here at ISTE NIT Durgapur, extend our heartfelt, solemn love and benevolence to all the martyrs and worship their immortalised contributions that glorifies our present day.

“Today, for the first time in our long and chequered history we find the whole of this vast land… brought together under the jurisdiction of one constitution and one union which takes over responsibility for the welfare of more than 320 million men and women who inhabit it”- Dr. Rajendra Prasad on January 26,1950

India officially gained independence from the British rule on August 15, 1947 after a brave fight by our freedom fighters. In spite of the so called freedom achieved by India, our country remained a constitutional monarchy under King George VI .Thus, there was an urgent need to draft and implement our own constitution. After almost three years and eleven sessions over a 165-day period the constitution was drafted by the 389-member Constituent Assembly. It was adopted on 26 November 1949 and became effective on 26 January 1950 thus, referred to as Republic Day. Each year, at the India Gate, the National Flag is unfurled by the President of India and later, parades are taken out at Rajpath, New Delhi.

On this note, ISTE NIT DURGAPUR would like to wish every Indian a very happy 73rd Republic Day to every Indian citizen.

#republicday #26january #india #indianflag #iste

"One individual may die for an idea, but that idea will, after his death, incarnate itself in a thousand lives."

Subhash Chandra Bose, a pre-eminent name among the Indian Freedom Fighters, and a personality who is notorious for being the leader of leaders. Despite being born in a privileged wealthy family, his acceptance towards reality made him choose a path full of hardships and immense struggle. In 1921, leaving behind the comfort of the Civil Service, he joined the nationalist movement. Seeking German and Japanese help, Bose revamped the Indian National Army. Earning the honorific “Netaji”, he became immortal among the hearts of every Indian.

Remembering him on his birth anniversary, we here at ISTE NIT Durgapur are indebted by the sacrifices he made for our country. Let us abide by our responsibilities, and make India a country he dreamt about.

#iste #23rdjan #netaji #netajijayanti #freedom #freedomfighter #azadhindfauj #subhashchandrabose #india

Makar Sankranti, also known as Maghi, Magh Bihu or Uttarayan, is observed on 14th or 15th January of every year to mark the transition day of Sun into the Capricorn. It marks the first day of the sun's transit into Makara rashi(Capricorn). 

According to the Hindu tradition, Makar Sankranti is dedicated to worshipping Lord Surya, the deity whose powers are essential for the existence of life on Earth. It is believed that Sankranti, after whom the festival is named, was a deity who killed a demon called Sankarasur. According to the Mahabharata, Bhishma Pitamah had waited for the sun to be in Uttarayana to embrace death. On this day, people take holy dip in the sacred water of rivers such as Ganga in the belief that this would absolve all their sins. It marks the beginning of the harvest season when people worship new crops and share them with delight. To celebrate the occasion, people perform charity by giving alms to the needy, fly kites, prepare sweets made of sesame and jaggery, worship livestock and more.

ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes all of you Happy Makar Sankranti and prays that may Lord Surya continue to bestow his blessings on each one of us and that we continue to thrive in harmony.

#happy #makarsankranti #celebration #maghi #maghubihu #uttarayan
